WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.229 --> 00:00:01.229
[applause]

00:00:01.229 --> 00:00:03.429
&gt;&gt;Jerry Holkins: Ok. Thank you.

00:00:03.429 --> 00:00:07.170
&gt;&gt;Mike Krahulik: We're happy to be here.

00:00:07.170 --> 00:00:16.600
&gt;&gt;Jerry Holkins: It only takes like 15 minutes
to get here so we can do this all the time.

00:00:16.600 --> 00:00:17.600
[laughter]

00:00:17.600 --> 00:00:18.600
Yeah, I mean where do you wanna -

00:00:18.600 --> 00:00:21.839
&gt;&gt;Mike Krahulik: We should start in 1998.
You need a fade wipe.

00:00:21.839 --> 00:00:23.009
[laughs]

00:00:23.009 --> 00:00:31.689
So in 1998 we were living together in Spokane
and making really horrible comic books.

00:00:31.689 --> 00:00:32.689
&gt;&gt;Jerry Holkins: Hey.

00:00:32.689 --> 00:00:35.899
&gt;&gt;Mike Krahulik: No, they were bad. And in
fact they were so bad that we would take them

00:00:35.899 --> 00:00:40.960
and leave them places, like in stores, hoping
that people would just pick them up and take

00:00:40.960 --> 00:00:41.960
them and read them.

00:00:41.960 --> 00:00:46.210
&gt;&gt;Jerry Holkins: You know when you go to Costco,
and there's like you can get little bits of

00:00:46.210 --> 00:00:47.210
an enchilada?

00:00:47.210 --> 00:00:48.210
[laughter]

00:00:48.210 --> 00:00:51.310
Sort of like a sample. Like we had this idea
for comics but no one wanted them. So -

00:00:51.310 --> 00:00:52.310
&gt;&gt;Mike Krahulik: Yeah.

00:00:52.310 --> 00:00:56.899
&gt;&gt;Jerry Holkins: So if you retain the metaphor,
it means our comics were disgusting. Oh, hey

00:00:56.899 --> 00:00:57.899
what's up.

00:00:57.899 --> 00:01:02.790
&gt;&gt;Mike Krahulik: And back then there was a
video game magazine called Next Generation.

00:01:02.790 --> 00:01:07.180
Most of you probably remember it if you've
been gaming for a while, and it was a pretty

00:01:07.180 --> 00:01:11.590
big deal at the time. I remember they posted
a little blurb saying that they were looking

00:01:11.590 --> 00:01:15.680
for a cartoonist to do a comic strip about
video games that they would then run in the

00:01:15.680 --> 00:01:16.680
magazine.

00:01:16.680 --> 00:01:20.820
&gt;&gt;Jerry Holkins: But here we have to emphasize
how things have changed. Because we all know

00:01:20.820 --> 00:01:22.130
about the Internet. Right?

00:01:22.130 --> 00:01:23.130
&gt;&gt;Mike Krahulik Yeah.

00:01:23.130 --> 00:01:27.550
&gt;&gt;Jerry Holkins: But this update he was talking
about, was on Next Generation online which

00:01:27.550 --> 00:01:32.800
was, you know, the online component of that
magazine. But it, you know, it being 1998,

00:01:32.800 --> 00:01:40.420
this is a gaming news website that updated
once a day, only weekdays at 7 pm.

00:01:40.420 --> 00:01:41.900
[laughter]

00:01:41.900 --> 00:01:43.520
And that was considered a lot of content.

00:01:43.520 --> 00:01:44.520
&gt;&gt;Mike Krahulik: Yeah.

00:01:44.520 --> 00:01:46.391
&gt;&gt;Jerry Holkins: It is not. It turns out.

00:01:46.391 --> 00:01:52.840
&gt;&gt;Mike Krahulik: So it was weird, but it wasn't
until that point that we'd even really considered

00:01:52.840 --> 00:01:58.840
the idea that maybe our love of games and
making comics, we could sort of combine those

00:01:58.840 --> 00:02:05.210
two things. And so, I made, I think, three
or four comics just on my own about, you know,

00:02:05.210 --> 00:02:10.119
the popular topics at the time which would
have been George Broussard and Prey.

00:02:10.119 --> 00:02:11.119
&gt;&gt;Jerry Holkins: Right.

00:02:11.119 --> 00:02:13.000
&gt;&gt;Mike Krahulik: I can't remember what the
hell the other one -

00:02:13.000 --> 00:02:14.510
&gt;&gt;Jerry Holkins: Truly eternal topics.

00:02:14.510 --> 00:02:22.640
&gt;&gt;Mike Krahulik: Yeah. You know, Doom. And
then I showed 'em to Jerry and he, he liked

00:02:22.640 --> 00:02:26.030
'em and he ended up writing a couple. And
so I think between the two of us we ended

00:02:26.030 --> 00:02:32.040
up with maybe five comics that we mailed into
Next Generation. And we never heard back,

00:02:32.040 --> 00:02:37.739
you know, weeks went by and I think even maybe
a month or so before I actually mailed them

00:02:37.739 --> 00:02:43.219
and said:"What happened with this, you know,
this comic contest." And they said: "Oh, you

00:02:43.219 --> 00:02:48.790
know, we got your material but we went with
a different cartoonist. We picked another

00:02:48.790 --> 00:02:49.790
winner."

00:02:49.790 --> 00:02:53.180
Another comic never appeared in Next Generation
magazine. So I'm assuming that they just wanted

00:02:53.180 --> 00:02:58.920
to get rid of us. But we had these comics
left over that we thought people should see.

00:02:58.920 --> 00:03:03.620
And that's when we decided to turn to the
Internet. At the time.

00:03:03.620 --> 00:03:05.069
&gt;&gt;Jerry Holkins: That's true.

00:03:05.069 --> 00:03:06.760
&gt;&gt;Mike Krahulik: That's your cue.

00:03:06.760 --> 00:03:10.930
&gt;&gt;Jerry Holkins: Oh. And so we essentially
offered them up. And again, and this is, is

00:03:10.930 --> 00:03:16.370
you know, there was a 'zine at the time. I
mean this was before the blog nomenclature,

00:03:16.370 --> 00:03:25.180
right? And so we essentially started that
we offered our comics to a 'zine called Loony

00:03:25.180 --> 00:03:28.590
Games, which was at that time an adjunct of
Blues News, which was a very, very big deal,

00:03:28.590 --> 00:03:31.069
you know, during that era.

00:03:31.069 --> 00:03:32.069
&gt;&gt;Mike Krahulik: Years ago.

00:03:32.069 --> 00:03:33.450
&gt;&gt;Jerry Holkins: Yeah, yeah. During the, you
know, the Mesozoic area.

00:03:33.450 --> 00:03:36.299
&gt;&gt;Mike Krahulik: Well we actually offered
them to pretty much every 'zine at the time.

00:03:36.299 --> 00:03:37.870
Like I remember sending them to Telefrag ?

00:03:37.870 --> 00:03:38.870
&gt;&gt;Jerry Holkins: Right.

00:03:38.870 --> 00:03:42.079
&gt;&gt;Mike Krahulik: and James Spy and all the
big gaming sites at the time.

00:03:42.079 --> 00:03:47.170
&gt;&gt;Jerry Holkins: Right. And we, so we sort
of felt that, that because it was low to the

00:03:47.170 --> 00:03:52.749
ground that this, this 'zine would be a good
venue for our stuff 'cause he wouldn't get

00:03:52.749 --> 00:03:58.120
in our way as much as a larger site might
have. In terms of the creative process. And

00:03:58.120 --> 00:03:59.170
that turned out to be incorrect.

00:03:59.170 --> 00:04:00.489
&gt;&gt;Mike Krahulik: [laughs]

00:04:00.489 --> 00:04:01.489
[laughter]

00:04:01.489 --> 00:04:05.579
&gt;&gt;Jerry Holkins: And, so is there a rating
for this discussion?

00:04:05.579 --> 00:04:06.870
&gt;&gt;Voice off stage: A rating?

00:04:06.870 --> 00:04:08.950
&gt;&gt;Jerry Holkins: Yes, i.e., PG, R.

00:04:08.950 --> 00:04:11.739
&gt;&gt;Voice off stage: Well it'll be public -

00:04:11.739 --> 00:04:16.000
&gt;&gt;Jerry Holkins: Well I don't care. People
know that I say bad words.

00:04:16.000 --> 00:04:17.230
[laughter]

00:04:17.230 --> 00:04:23.790
I'm saying, I'm saying does that make, does
that make things complicated for you if I

00:04:23.790 --> 00:04:24.840
say the word "fuck."

00:04:24.840 --> 00:04:25.840
[laughter]

00:04:25.840 --> 00:04:27.130
&gt;&gt;Mike Krahulik: No, see you messed that up.
Because ?

00:04:27.130 --> 00:04:30.440
&gt;&gt;Jerry Holkins: Oh, I should have done it
the other way around.

00:04:30.440 --> 00:04:31.440
[laughter]

00:04:31.440 --> 00:04:36.750
&gt;&gt;Jerry Holkins: Anyway, here listen now that
you know what word I said, understand that

00:04:36.750 --> 00:04:41.880
that's where all the problems came from. Because
we thought that that was a very funny word.

00:04:41.880 --> 00:04:45.180
And I can tell by your reaction that you too
were amused by it.

00:04:45.180 --> 00:04:46.180
[laughter]

00:04:46.180 --> 00:04:51.070
But our quote unquote editor felt that profanity
was unnecessary in humor, which is a lie.

00:04:51.070 --> 00:04:53.221
&gt;&gt;Mike Krahulik: He told us, he flat out -

00:04:53.221 --> 00:04:54.221
&gt;&gt;Jerry Holkins: A black lie.

00:04:54.221 --> 00:04:56.480
&gt;&gt;Mike Krahulik: He told us that that word
was not funny and that we should not use it

00:04:56.480 --> 00:04:58.500
anymore. And that's, I think, when we decided

00:04:58.500 --> 00:04:59.500
&gt;&gt;Jerry Holkins: That was ?

00:04:59.500 --> 00:05:00.630
&gt;&gt;Mike Krahulik: to get our own effing website.

00:05:00.630 --> 00:05:01.630
[laughter]

00:05:01.630 --> 00:05:02.630
&gt;&gt;Jerry Holkins: Yeah.

00:05:02.630 --> 00:05:03.790
&gt;&gt;Voice off stage: That's better.

00:05:03.790 --> 00:05:07.850
&gt;&gt;Jerry Holkins: Yeah. And I made some, you
know, I code it as classy.

00:05:07.850 --> 00:05:08.850
&gt;&gt;Mike Krahulik: That's how I do it.

00:05:08.850 --> 00:05:11.640
&gt;&gt;Jerry Holkins: And I, you know, so we started
to host it elsewhere which was, you know,

00:05:11.640 --> 00:05:14.900
and at the time was a byzantine process. But
I wrote some -

00:05:14.900 --> 00:05:18.910
&gt;&gt;Mike Krahulik: The reality is that we gave
Loony Games those six comics under the assumption

00:05:18.910 --> 00:05:23.880
that he would run those comics and then that
would be it. And then, you know, the next

00:05:23.880 --> 00:05:27.390
Monday came, he'd been putting them up once
a week and said: "Need the comic for today.

00:05:27.390 --> 00:05:31.830
Where's it at?" We're like, "Well we didn't
sign any kind of agreement to make more of

00:05:31.830 --> 00:05:32.830
these."

00:05:32.830 --> 00:05:34.900
&gt;&gt;Jerry Holkins: It was never our intention.
We simply had made something - it would be

00:05:34.900 --> 00:05:39.390
like if you made a delicious meal and then
it was just sitting there on the stove. Like

00:05:39.390 --> 00:05:41.730
we wanted people to sample
our wares.

00:05:41.730 --> 00:05:46.410
&gt;&gt;Mike Krahulik: And it was really just us
not wanting to disappoint him that made us

00:05:46.410 --> 00:05:47.410
keep doing it.

00:05:47.410 --> 00:05:48.410
&gt;&gt;Jerry Holkins: It was social anxiety.

00:05:48.410 --> 00:05:49.410
&gt;&gt;Mike Krahulik: Yeah.

00:05:49.410 --> 00:05:50.410
&gt;&gt;Jerry Holkins: Actually.

00:05:50.410 --> 00:05:51.600
&gt;&gt;Mike Krahulik: Um. Yeah. That was it.

00:05:51.600 --> 00:05:54.611
&gt;&gt;Jerry Holkins: Oh. Okay. And so we started
doing our own thing.

00:05:54.611 --> 00:05:59.110
I was able to - I managed to write a set of
frames in HTML ?

00:05:59.110 --> 00:06:00.110
&gt;&gt;Mike Krahulik: [laughs]

00:06:00.110 --> 00:06:05.850
&gt;&gt;Jerry Holkins: which included some incredibly
large navigation buttons. And the navigation,

00:06:05.850 --> 00:06:11.520
the navigation buttons were so large that
the scaling kept creating this huge field

00:06:11.520 --> 00:06:17.670
on the left where no content was. And it was
agitating to me from an aesthetics perspective.

00:06:17.670 --> 00:06:25.590
And so I started writing, you know, essentially
news posts to a company, the strip for that

00:06:25.590 --> 00:06:31.260
day. Just the different topics that we were
discussing and now that's a core part of the

00:06:31.260 --> 00:06:34.930
site.
Now the idea that the comic includes commentary

00:06:34.930 --> 00:06:39.890
that may or may not be about gaming, or you
know, it might be about a sandwich that I

00:06:39.890 --> 00:06:44.900
had, and thought was great. But all that stuff
the way that that works, is that I was just

00:06:44.900 --> 00:06:50.180
trying to fill that - there was just a void
in the template. And we weren't even, we didn't

00:06:50.180 --> 00:06:55.860
even archive them. Like for three years I
just, you know, select, delete, -

00:06:55.860 --> 00:06:56.880
&gt;&gt;Mike Krahulik: [laughs]

00:06:56.880 --> 00:06:59.961
&gt;&gt;Jerry Holkins: right out of the raw HTML
file. So -

00:06:59.961 --> 00:07:02.730
&gt;&gt;Mike Krahulik: Yeah. Those were good days.

00:07:02.730 --> 00:07:07.610
&gt;&gt;Jerry Holkins: Yeah. But, I mean that just,
that just is an assertion that we did not,

00:07:07.610 --> 00:07:12.720
we had no idea what we had made. I think that
other people sensed that -

00:07:12.720 --> 00:07:13.730
&gt;&gt;Mike Krahulik: Well, the other people did

00:07:13.730 --> 00:07:14.750
&gt;&gt;Jerry Holkins: we were on to something.

00:07:14.750 --> 00:07:16.440
&gt;&gt;Mike Krahulik: Yeah. In fact that the next
leg of our journey ?

00:07:16.440 --> 00:07:17.440
takes us -

00:07:17.440 --> 00:07:19.740
&gt;&gt;Jerry Holkins: - At the bar table. Buyers.

00:07:19.740 --> 00:07:23.940
&gt;&gt;Mike Krahulik: Yeah. So now we're on the
Internet and we have a website and people

00:07:23.940 --> 00:07:31.400
are coming to it. And you might remember back
in these days the concept of content aggregators.

00:07:31.400 --> 00:07:36.960
The idea that a company like a UGO or something
might just buy up a couple thousand websites

00:07:36.960 --> 00:07:38.840
and then run ads across their entire network.

00:07:38.840 --> 00:07:43.620
&gt;&gt;Jerry Holkins: But that suffix the gator
suffix and its implications of a reptilian

00:07:43.620 --> 00:07:45.310
carnivore will come back.

00:07:45.310 --> 00:07:46.310
&gt;&gt;Mike Krahulik: [laughter]

00:07:46.310 --> 00:07:47.310
&gt;&gt;Jerry Holkins: Later on. You'll see it.

00:07:47.310 --> 00:07:53.000
&gt;&gt;Mike Krahulik: So we actually got approached
by a content aggregator named, I forget already.

00:07:53.000 --> 00:07:55.500
&gt;&gt;Jerry Holkins: Jackasses Incorporated.

00:07:55.500 --> 00:07:56.500
[laughter]

00:07:56.500 --> 00:07:57.840
&gt;&gt;Mike Krahulik: Let's just, let's -

00:07:57.840 --> 00:07:58.840
&gt;&gt;Jerry Holkins: No. Let's use a euphemism.

00:07:58.840 --> 00:08:00.380
&gt;&gt;Mike Krahulik: Who was it? What was the
name of them?

00:08:00.380 --> 00:08:01.460
&gt;&gt;Male voice off stage: Was it eFront?

00:08:01.460 --> 00:08:05.930
&gt;&gt;Mike Krahulik: eFront. Thank you, sir. I
try to block that out as much as I can. And

00:08:05.930 --> 00:08:10.710
they wanted to, they wanted to add Penny Arcade
to their network and run ads and they promised

00:08:10.710 --> 00:08:14.410
us all this money and said: "You quit your
jobs and you can do this full time and -

00:08:14.410 --> 00:08:16.280
&gt;&gt;Jerry Holkins: Oh, and we got stock.

00:08:16.280 --> 00:08:17.280
&gt;&gt;Mike Krahulik: Oh yeah, we got eFront stock.
Hey.

00:08:17.280 --> 00:08:19.950
[laughter]

00:08:19.950 --> 00:08:24.721
And so we ended up signing the agreement.
And, you know, we didn't realize that what

00:08:24.721 --> 00:08:30.760
we were signing was actually the rights to
Penny Arcade. So we actually literally sold

00:08:30.760 --> 00:08:38.829
Penny Arcade to eFront, for some worthless
stock and the promise of advertising revenue.

00:08:38.829 --> 00:08:39.830
Right? And basically, that's what we did.

00:08:39.830 --> 00:08:42.480
&gt;&gt;Jerry Holkins: Yeah. That's more or less.
But I mean the document - it's like we had

00:08:42.480 --> 00:08:46.800
a different conception about what that document
represented. I mean, for us that document

00:08:46.800 --> 00:08:53.360
represented the ability to create comics full
time which was an incredible concept. And

00:08:53.360 --> 00:08:56.959
it's entirely possible we would have given
up almost anything do, you know, to do that.

00:08:56.959 --> 00:08:58.569
And we did. But it was inadvertent.

00:08:58.569 --> 00:09:02.389
&gt;Mike Krahulik: Yeah. [laughs] And you know,
and they actually made good on the promise.

00:09:02.389 --> 00:09:06.730
For the first couple months they did send
us checks and, you know, I did quit Circuit

00:09:06.730 --> 00:09:07.730
City.

00:09:07.730 --> 00:09:10.000
&gt;&gt;Jerry Holkins: This is that period when
the Internet was just totally rad -

00:09:10.000 --> 00:09:13.620
&gt;&gt;Mike Krahulik: Yeah. People were just throwing'
money at 'ya. And so I remember it was like,

00:09:13.620 --> 00:09:18.850
you know, Christmas Eve and I think my manager
at Circuit City told me to go do wire maintenance

00:09:18.850 --> 00:09:23.312
on the laptops and I just said: "F you." And
I walked out.

00:09:23.312 --> 00:09:24.312
[laughter]

00:09:24.312 --> 00:09:26.320
And, you know, it was pretty much right after
that eFront stopped sending checks.

00:09:26.320 --> 00:09:27.320
[laughter]

00:09:27.320 --> 00:09:29.310
So that was poor timing on my part.

00:09:29.310 --> 00:09:30.310
[laughter]

00:09:30.310 --> 00:09:36.920
But yeah, so they stopped sending the money
and then when we asked them where the money

00:09:36.920 --> 00:09:41.279
was, they said that they needed to put more
ads on the site. And so eventually it got

00:09:41.279 --> 00:09:44.999
to the point where it was just ads on the
site, and I think at one point if you go back

00:09:44.999 --> 00:09:49.680
through the archive you'll see a comic very
early on that is just an ad. That was our

00:09:49.680 --> 00:09:53.199
sort of, us fighting back like we thought
"Well you've taken over every other part of

00:09:53.199 --> 00:09:54.980
the frickin' site, you might as well -

00:09:54.980 --> 00:09:57.889
&gt;&gt;Jerry Holkins: And we also introduced a
character named, Mr. Adbannerhead.

00:09:57.889 --> 00:09:58.949
&gt;&gt;Mike Krahulik: [laughs] Yeah.

00:09:58.949 --> 00:10:02.279
&gt;&gt;Jerry Holkins: Which was just a subtle dig
at that policy.

00:10:02.279 --> 00:10:08.779
&gt;&gt;Mike Krahulik: We were frustrated at the
time. And so we said: "Listen this isn't working.

00:10:08.779 --> 00:10:12.420
We'll just take our comic and go." And that's
when we realized that we couldn't just take

00:10:12.420 --> 00:10:17.870
our comic and go, because it was their comic.
[laughs] It was bad. And they were actually

00:10:17.870 --> 00:10:18.870
gonna fire us.

00:10:18.870 --> 00:10:22.459
&gt;&gt;Jerry Holkins: Yeah. Oh and see 'cause and
this is great. So you knew about eFront, but

00:10:22.459 --> 00:10:25.480
I mean do you know that all the ICQ, remember
ICQ -

00:10:25.480 --> 00:10:26.480
&gt;&gt;Mike Krahulik: [laughs]

00:10:26.480 --> 00:10:30.720
&gt;&gt;Jerry Holkins: There were all the ICQ logs
that came out so they used a lot of ICQ in

00:10:30.720 --> 00:10:37.089
upper echelons of eFront. And all their conversations
about us came to light after the company started

00:10:37.089 --> 00:10:42.449
to have trouble; and it's really strange reading
about yourself in the third person. Like,

00:10:42.449 --> 00:10:46.089
you know, it's like opening a book and like
finding out that you're actually incorporated

00:10:46.089 --> 00:10:47.420
into some grand drama.

00:10:47.420 --> 00:10:48.420
&gt;&gt;Mike Krahulik: [laughs] Yeah.

00:10:48.420 --> 00:10:53.980
&gt;&gt;Jerry Holkins: Because they had every intention
of firing us from our own comic and then having

00:10:53.980 --> 00:10:55.100
other people produce it.

00:10:55.100 --> 00:10:59.300
&gt;&gt;Mike Krahulik: Yeah, in fact if you, if
you do a search for ICQ logs eFront, you can

00:10:59.300 --> 00:11:03.339
still find the logs and they're incredible.
But the conversations about Penny Arcade,

00:11:03.339 --> 00:11:07.981
I mean, were very far along - they had a new
artist. They had comics done and they were

00:11:07.981 --> 00:11:14.600
ready to fire us. Had their president not
been under investigation for, like some kind

00:11:14.600 --> 00:11:15.600
of like racketeering -

00:11:15.600 --> 00:11:16.600
&gt;&gt;Jerry Holkins: Yeah. He had to flee to country
 -

00:11:16.600 --> 00:11:17.600
&gt;&gt;Mike Krahulik: Tax evasion.

00:11:17.600 --> 00:11:18.600
&gt;&gt;Jerry Holkins: Yeah.

00:11:18.600 --> 00:11:19.600
&gt;&gt;Mike Krahulik: And ended up leaving to Africa.

00:11:19.600 --> 00:11:20.600
[laughter]

00:11:20.600 --> 00:11:24.820
&gt;&gt;Mike Krahulik: We were, we were that close.
And, and so it was at that point that the

00:11:24.820 --> 00:11:28.930
company sort of dissolved under all these
legal problems that we said: "Okay, listen

00:11:28.930 --> 00:11:33.850
you guys owe us a ton of money. Instead of
giving us cash, which we know you don' have,

00:11:33.850 --> 00:11:39.800
just give us our comic back." And that's the
only way we were able to get out of it.

00:11:39.800 --> 00:11:41.600
&gt;&gt;Jerry Holkins: Right.

00:11:41.600 --> 00:11:43.430
That's true. I'm sorry. I'm like sweating,
like my -

00:11:43.430 --> 00:11:44.430
&gt;&gt;Mike Krahulik: [laughs]

00:11:44.430 --> 00:11:46.451
&gt;&gt;Jerry Holkins: My heart rate has increased
as a result of that retelling.

00:11:46.451 --> 00:11:47.451
&gt;&gt;Mike Krahulik: That was, that was a very
scary time.

00:11:47.451 --> 00:11:48.970
&gt;&gt;Jerry Holkins: [sighs heavily]

00:11:48.970 --> 00:11:54.610
&gt;&gt;Mike Krahulik: It was also the time that
we accidentally sold the book rights - for

00:11:54.610 --> 00:11:58.120
five years to a man who took all our money
and moved to Alaska.

00:11:58.120 --> 00:11:59.120
[laughter]

00:11:59.120 --> 00:12:02.470
So, I mean, that's a different story though,
and we made, we made a lot of bad decisions.

00:12:02.470 --> 00:12:03.689
&gt;&gt;Jerry Holkins: Right. Early on.

00:12:03.689 --> 00:12:08.410
&gt;&gt;Mike Krahulik: We made bad decisions until
we found someone to make good decisions on

00:12:08.410 --> 00:12:09.410
our behalf.

00:12:09.410 --> 00:12:14.809
&gt;&gt;Jerry Holkins: On our behalf. Which is who,
who is now sort of, he sort of runs Penny

00:12:14.809 --> 00:12:19.410
Arcade. Like the business side of Penny Arcade.
We eventually realized, you know, due to the

00:12:19.410 --> 00:12:23.649
stories that we have just told you, and other
stories which we have not yet related -

00:12:23.649 --> 00:12:25.170
[laughter]

00:12:25.170 --> 00:12:30.019
we decided that we were not business people.
That the best we could do, the best we could

00:12:30.019 --> 00:12:35.930
do, in this life was to create three jpegs
a week. That was the extent of our capabilities.

00:12:35.930 --> 00:12:36.930
[laughter]

00:12:36.930 --> 00:12:38.999
and we decided not to reach for the stars.

00:12:38.999 --> 00:12:43.999
&gt;&gt;Mike Krahulik: At this point, you know,
so eFront stopped paying us - we've both quit

00:12:43.999 --> 00:12:46.860
our jobs - we're at the VA.

00:12:46.860 --> 00:12:47.860
&gt;&gt;Jerry Holkins: We're -

00:12:47.860 --> 00:12:50.481
&gt;&gt;Mike Krahulik: Yeah. And I remember having
a conversation with Jerry where I said: "Okay.

00:12:50.481 --> 00:12:56.389
Well, do we go back to our jobs and quit doing
Penny Arcade or do we, do we try to figure

00:12:56.389 --> 00:13:00.769
out some other way to make this work?" And
it just so happened that literally that day

00:13:00.769 --> 00:13:05.319
I had gotten an email from a reader who was
telling me about the Amazon honor system.

00:13:05.319 --> 00:13:11.369
And it had just come out that week and it
was a system where readers could donate money

00:13:11.369 --> 00:13:12.939
to you for nothing.

00:13:12.939 --> 00:13:14.990
&gt;&gt;Jerry Holkins: It's just a transactional
system similar -

00:13:14.990 --> 00:13:15.990
&gt;&gt;Mike Krahulik: It's a tip jar for your website.

00:13:15.990 --> 00:13:17.100
&gt;&gt;Jerry Holkins: Yeah, sort of like PayPal,
the way PayPal works.

00:13:17.100 --> 00:13:22.879
&gt;&gt;Mike Krahulik: Yeah. And we, you know, in
our heads running the numbers, which we can't

00:13:22.879 --> 00:13:26.201
run. We thought "Okay, well if we have" -

00:13:26.201 --> 00:13:27.350
&gt;&gt;Jerry Holkins: remember what the number
was?

00:13:27.350 --> 00:13:31.819
&gt;&gt;Mike Krahulik: If we have 50 thousand readers
and each one of them gives us one dollar everyday

00:13:31.819 --> 00:13:32.819
like ?

00:13:32.819 --> 00:13:33.819
[laughter]

00:13:33.819 --> 00:13:35.930
&gt;&gt;Mike Krahulik: we're like we're gonna be
bijillionaires!

00:13:35.930 --> 00:13:36.930
[laughter]

00:13:36.930 --> 00:13:39.860
And so, you know, we put the tip jar up, and
we weren't bijillionaires. You know,

00:13:39.860 --> 00:13:46.329
&gt;&gt;Jerry Holkins: Listen we weren't bizillionaires,
but it is a fact that after a single day of,

00:13:46.329 --> 00:13:49.050
of requests for donations there was ten thousand
dollars in there.

00:13:49.050 --> 00:13:54.240
&gt;&gt;Mike Krahulik: Yeah. And it ended up that
we said "Okay, how much money do you and I

00:13:54.240 --> 00:13:59.970
need to live? Rent? Groceries? Video games?"
Take that number -

00:13:59.970 --> 00:14:01.550
&gt;&gt;Jerry Holkins: It's a part of a food pyramid.

00:14:01.550 --> 00:14:02.550
[laughter]

00:14:02.550 --> 00:14:03.550
&gt;&gt;Mike Krahulik: Yeah.

00:14:03.550 --> 00:14:04.550
[laughter]

00:14:04.550 --> 00:14:06.670
And we took that number and we put it on the
website and we said: "Dear reader: This is

00:14:06.670 --> 00:14:08.509
how much we need to live."

00:14:08.509 --> 00:14:09.509
[laughter]

00:14:09.509 --> 00:14:10.610
"Please give us this."

00:14:10.610 --> 00:14:16.040
&gt;&gt;Jerry Holkins: It was essentially like an
NPR type, you know, public media sort of thing.

00:14:16.040 --> 00:14:17.040
I mean, that's -

00:14:17.040 --> 00:14:20.370
&gt;&gt;Mike Krahulik: Yeah. We were very honest.
We constantly showed the graph of - here's

00:14:20.370 --> 00:14:23.480
how much we need or we'll starve to death.
And here's where we are.

00:14:23.480 --> 00:14:26.029
&gt;&gt;Jerry Holkins: Right. There's still gonna
be some kind of benefit.

00:14:26.029 --> 00:14:28.619
&gt;&gt;Mike Krahulik: Yeah. Wow. Is that the Internet
archive or -

00:14:28.619 --> 00:14:29.619
&gt;&gt;Jerry Holkins: Yes, exactly.

00:14:29.619 --> 00:14:30.619
&gt;&gt;&gt;Mike Krahulik: or way back machine?

00:14:30.619 --> 00:14:31.619
&gt;&gt;Jerry Holkins: Yeah. See he has, he has
our thermometer.

00:14:31.619 --> 00:14:35.540
&gt;&gt;Mike Krahulik: Yeah. And we gave away little
prizes when, you know, we reached our goal.

00:14:35.540 --> 00:14:37.300
&gt;&gt;Jerry Holkins: Sort of like the fair. Yeah.
You know -

00:14:37.300 --> 00:14:39.639
&gt;&gt;Mike Krahulik: Sustaining our lives apparently
we thought wasn't enough. They're gonna need

00:14:39.639 --> 00:14:41.139
a jpeg too.

00:14:41.139 --> 00:14:42.139
[laughter]

00:14:42.139 --> 00:14:43.139
Not enough that we fed ourselves.

00:14:43.139 --> 00:14:44.139
&gt;&gt;Jerry Holkins: It's sort of our line though
 - jpegs.

00:14:44.139 --> 00:14:47.850
&gt;&gt;Mike Krahulik: Yeah. And that did it for
 -

00:14:47.850 --> 00:14:48.889
&gt;Jerry Holkins: Year and a half.

00:14:48.889 --> 00:14:50.162
&gt;&gt;Mike Krahulik: A year and a half.

00:14:50.162 --> 00:14:54.199
&gt;&gt;Jerry Holkins: And then eventually, we sort
of got the sense - cause we were married at

00:14:54.199 --> 00:14:55.199
this time -

00:14:55.199 --> 00:14:56.199
&gt;&gt;Mike Krahulik: [laughs]

00:14:56.199 --> 00:14:57.199
&gt;&gt;Jerry Holkins: We got the sense that -

00:14:57.199 --> 00:14:58.199
&gt;&gt;Mike Krahulik: Yeah.

00:14:58.199 --> 00:15:01.690
&gt;&gt;Jerry Holkins: We got the sense relying
the Internet, relying on -

00:15:01.690 --> 00:15:02.889
&gt;&gt;Mike Krahulik: The generosity of strangers
 ?

00:15:02.889 --> 00:15:06.649
&gt;&gt;Jerry Holkins: Was not a strong strategy.

00:15:06.649 --> 00:15:09.352
&gt;&gt;Mike Krahulik: It's a tough sell domestically.
Let's say that.

00:15:09.352 --> 00:15:12.660
[laughter]
When your wife wants to know, you know, where

00:15:12.660 --> 00:15:14.990
the check is coming from and you say -

00:15:14.990 --> 00:15:16.009
&gt;&gt;Jerry Holkins: "The Internet."

00:15:16.009 --> 00:15:17.009
[laughter]

00:15:17.009 --> 00:15:19.819
&gt;&gt;Mike Krahulik: People. Alright. Deal with
it. "Will we have enough to make the rent?"

00:15:19.819 --> 00:15:24.749
I don't know yet. Listen it's only the 15th,
honey, I mean, don't you see my graph.

00:15:24.749 --> 00:15:25.749
[laughter]

00:15:25.749 --> 00:15:28.480
&gt;&gt;Jerry Holkins: I cannot believe we got -

00:15:28.480 --> 00:15:32.629
&gt;&gt;Mike Krahulik: They should never have gone
along with that plan as long as they did.

00:15:32.629 --> 00:15:33.629
Yeah.

00:15:33.629 --> 00:15:37.839
&gt;&gt;Jerry Holkins: Long suffering. But, so,
shortly thereafter we received an email from

00:15:37.839 --> 00:15:43.579
someone who wanted to talk to us about a business
opportunity. And I think that we all get mails

00:15:43.579 --> 00:15:44.579
that -

00:15:44.579 --> 00:15:48.720
&gt;&gt;Mike Krahulik: [laughs]
that describe the contours of a business opportunity

00:15:48.720 --> 00:15:50.619
with some frequency. Sometimes from Nigeria.

00:15:50.619 --> 00:15:51.939
&gt;&gt;Mike Krahulik: Yeah.

00:15:51.939 --> 00:15:52.960
&gt;&gt;Jerry Holkins: And so -

00:15:52.960 --> 00:15:54.079
&gt;&gt;Mike Krahulik: We disregarded it.

00:15:54.079 --> 00:15:58.689
&gt;&gt;Jerry Holkins: Yeah. Exactly. And then he
wrote us back saying that he would take us

00:15:58.689 --> 00:16:01.040
to lunch and, and it turned around.

00:16:01.040 --> 00:16:02.759
&gt;&gt;Mike Krahulik: Yeah. We perked up at that
point.

00:16:02.759 --> 00:16:03.759
[laughter]

00:16:03.759 --> 00:16:04.759
&gt;&gt;Jerry Holkins: Yeah.

00:16:04.759 --> 00:16:09.989
&gt;&gt;Mike Krahulik: Yeah. The concept of a free
lunch - literally a free lunch - got us interested.

00:16:09.989 --> 00:16:12.670
That was the only reason we met with Robert.

00:16:12.670 --> 00:16:18.269
&gt;&gt;Jerry Holkins: Right. And so we did meet
him and he was able to quickly ascertain - being

00:16:18.269 --> 00:16:22.800
a person of more than average intelligence
 - that we were idiots.

00:16:22.800 --> 00:16:23.800
[laughter]

00:16:23.800 --> 00:16:26.600
&gt;&gt;Mike Krahulik: Yeah. He was at the time
running, working for a consulting company

00:16:26.600 --> 00:16:31.850
and one of their consultants - consultantees?
consulters?

00:16:31.850 --> 00:16:32.850
&gt;&gt;Jerry Holkins: Consulters.

00:16:32.850 --> 00:16:36.889
&gt;&gt;Mike Krahulik: One of the companies they
were consulting for was a video game company,

00:16:36.889 --> 00:16:40.119
and his idea for them was that they should
advertise on Penny Arcade.

00:16:40.119 --> 00:16:41.680
&gt;&gt;Jerry Holkins: He was a reader. He loved
the comic.

00:16:41.680 --> 00:16:44.649
&gt;&gt;Mike Krahulik: Yeah. And it was at this
point that we just started sort of trying

00:16:44.649 --> 00:16:50.019
to transition from simply donations to also
doing advertising. And believe it or not,

00:16:50.019 --> 00:16:52.709
I was actually the one that got pegged as
being the business guy.

00:16:52.709 --> 00:16:55.389
&gt;&gt;Jerry Holkins: Yes, no doubt. But it changed
after Saga -

00:16:55.389 --> 00:16:56.910
&gt;&gt;Male voice from audience: Yes.

00:16:56.910 --> 00:17:01.439
&gt;&gt;Mike Krahulik: So we ended up, I ended up
calling up - through a number of sources I

00:17:01.439 --> 00:17:05.390
got a phone number for Saga - and I thought
this would be great. They have - we love their

00:17:05.390 --> 00:17:08.490
games - they're gonna want to advertise on
our site.

00:17:08.490 --> 00:17:09.490
&gt;&gt;Jerry Holkins: They called John Saga.

00:17:09.490 --> 00:17:12.940
&gt;&gt;Mike K: [laughs] Yeah. And I remember we
talked about it trying to decide - well how

00:17:12.940 --> 00:17:18.059
much should we charge for an advertising slot
on Penny Arcade? And we, we came to the idea

00:17:18.059 --> 00:17:21.299
that one thousand dollars for a month of advertising
would be pretty hot.

00:17:21.299 --> 00:17:22.939
&gt;&gt;Jerry Holkins: That's a lot of money.

00:17:22.939 --> 00:17:27.459
&gt;&gt;Mike Krahulik: And I'm not gonna detail
the conversation I had with Saga's very nice

00:17:27.459 --> 00:17:32.721
marketing lady, but in the end she ended up
paying two hundred dollars. So I'm not a great

00:17:32.721 --> 00:17:37.510
business person, at all. It was horrible.
She just destroyed me over the phone until

00:17:37.510 --> 00:17:40.779
I was crying and said I'd take whatever she
wanted to pay us.

00:17:40.779 --> 00:17:41.779
[laughter]

00:17:41.779 --> 00:17:42.830
But we got those ads for "18-wheeler".

00:17:42.830 --> 00:17:43.830
&gt;&gt;Jerry Holkins: That's right.

00:17:43.830 --> 00:17:44.830
&gt;&gt;Mike Krahulik: You know.

00:17:44.830 --> 00:17:45.830
&gt;&gt;Jerry Holkins: Right.

00:17:45.830 --> 00:17:49.830
&lt;&lt;Mike Krahulik: And so Robert could see that
we had no idea what we were doing. It's just

00:17:49.830 --> 00:17:50.830
obvious to him.

00:17:50.830 --> 00:17:55.770
&gt;&gt;Jerry Holkins: Yeah. We had huge problems.
And it, it happened that, I mean, so the next

00:17:55.770 --> 00:17:59.630
time that he, he wanted to start having weekly
meetings with us. And, but these meetings

00:17:59.630 --> 00:18:03.470
included lunch. And so we continued to attend
them.

00:18:03.470 --> 00:18:04.470
[laughter]

00:18:04.470 --> 00:18:09.240
And he would, we would eat turkey and he would
hold forth and this is a great scenario.

00:18:09.240 --> 00:18:12.190
&gt;&gt;Mike Krahulik: Remember, remember he asked
us what our ten year plan was? [laughs]

00:18:12.190 --> 00:18:13.309
&gt;&gt;Jerry Holkins: Yeah. Yeah.

00:18:13.309 --> 00:18:16.250
&gt;&gt;Mike Krahulik: We didn't have an afternoon
plan.

00:18:16.250 --> 00:18:17.250
[laughter]

00:18:17.250 --> 00:18:19.480
&gt;&gt;Jerry Holkins: Yeah. Our plan - the current
plan was on the plate.

00:18:19.480 --> 00:18:20.480
&gt;&gt;Mike Krahulik: Yeah. And

00:18:20.480 --> 00:18:23.370
&gt;&gt;Jerry Holkins: And after we managed that
we were gonna try to come up with a new scenario.

00:18:23.370 --> 00:18:24.370
[laughter]

00:18:24.370 --> 00:18:28.390
But, you know, though one of these meetings
 - one of those ill-fated meetings - he came

00:18:28.390 --> 00:18:32.929
and he just laid a piece of paper down on
the table and said "This is a five year plan.

00:18:32.929 --> 00:18:38.309
I will - I'm gonna quit my job. I'm gonna
work for you guys for free for three months

00:18:38.309 --> 00:18:43.640
and if I can't, if I can't pay my way then
I'll quit and you guys can go back to doing

00:18:43.640 --> 00:18:46.190
what you were doing before." And, um -

00:18:46.190 --> 00:18:48.149
&gt;&gt;Mike Krahulik: It worked out pretty good.

00:18:48.149 --> 00:18:49.149
&gt;&gt;Jerry Holkins: Yeah.

00:18:49.149 --> 00:18:50.149
[laughter]

00:18:50.149 --> 00:18:51.149
&gt;&gt;Mike Krahulik: He did a good job. It turns
out.

00:18:51.149 --> 00:18:54.950
&gt;&gt;Jerry Holkins: Just as an index - as an
index of his organizational might - I mean

00:18:54.950 --> 00:18:58.520
the first, the first PAX he put together in
three months.

00:18:58.520 --> 00:19:00.040
&gt;&gt;Mike Krahulik: That's pretty incredible.

00:19:00.040 --> 00:19:04.090
&gt;&gt;Jerry Holkins: I mean he put together a
gaming convention which is now more or less

00:19:04.090 --> 00:19:08.940
seen as, as you know, the you know, quote
unquote consumer, right? But I'm not super

00:19:08.940 --> 00:19:13.600
enthusiastic about that kind of terminology.
A gaming convention, you know, that is the

00:19:13.600 --> 00:19:18.169
pride of the Western Hemisphere. It had its
genesis in a three month plan by Robert.

00:19:18.169 --> 00:19:24.270
&gt;&gt;Mike Krahulik: Yeah. So - so he came on
board and, and started really trying to actually

00:19:24.270 --> 00:19:28.840
spin up an advertising, like a revenue stream,
I guess it what he calls it.

00:19:28.840 --> 00:19:29.840
&lt;&lt;Jerry Holkins: Yes. Multiple streams.

00:19:29.840 --> 00:19:30.840
&gt;&gt;Mike Krahulik: Revenue river.

00:19:30.840 --> 00:19:31.840
&gt;&gt;Jerry Holkins: He wanted to diversify.

00:19:31.840 --> 00:19:32.899
&gt;&gt;Mike Krahulik: Yeah. And have synergy.

00:19:32.899 --> 00:19:33.899
[laughter]

00:19:33.899 --> 00:19:39.120
And so as soon as he started getting ads on
the site, we thought that it just wasn't appropriate

00:19:39.120 --> 00:19:40.120
to do the -

00:19:40.120 --> 00:19:41.120
&gt;&gt;Jerry Holkins: The donation -

00:19:41.120 --> 00:19:44.710
&gt;&gt;Mike Krahulik: the donations anymore. So
it was right when Robert came on and the ads

00:19:44.710 --> 00:19:49.080
started working that we dropped the honor
system. But like I said that had worked for

00:19:49.080 --> 00:19:55.830
a year and a half. And so Robert came on.
He got the advertising working. He got merchandise

00:19:55.830 --> 00:20:01.169
working. All the stuff that we couldn't do
 - he did. And it allowed us to really just

00:20:01.169 --> 00:20:06.830
focus on making comics. Which was all we could
ever do anyway. [laughs] It was really the

00:20:06.830 --> 00:20:08.929
best thing that could have happened for Penny
Arcade.

00:20:08.929 --> 00:20:09.929
&gt;&gt;Jerry Holkins: Right.

00:20:09.929 --> 00:20:10.929
[pause]

00:20:10.929 --> 00:20:11.929
That's it.

00:20:11.929 --> 00:20:12.929
&gt;&gt;Mike Krahulik: [laughs}

00:20:12.929 --> 00:20:15.940
&gt;&gt;Jerry Holkins: I mean more or less, that's
it.

00:20:15.940 --> 00:20:21.750
&lt;&lt;Mike Krahulik: Yeah. So after a while we'd
been going to a lot of conventions around

00:20:21.750 --> 00:20:27.269
the country - some of them like in school
gymnasiums. I mean we went everywhere. Did

00:20:27.269 --> 00:20:31.570
all kinds of shows. But we realized that every
one of these shows that we went to, was almost

00:20:31.570 --> 00:20:36.270
always comics and maybe they would have like
a little bit of a gaming corner annex -

00:20:36.270 --> 00:20:37.570
&lt;&lt;Jerry Holkins: Ghetto.

00:20:37.570 --> 00:20:41.080
&gt;&gt;Mike Krahulik: Ghetto. There, where they
had like an Xbox. Or it was all anime and

00:20:41.080 --> 00:20:42.690
they would have a little gaming section.

00:20:42.690 --> 00:20:43.690
&gt;&gt;Jerry Holkins: Right.

00:20:43.690 --> 00:20:47.450
&gt;&gt;Mike Krahulik: We though why isn't anyone
making a gaming convention. Like this sort

00:20:47.450 --> 00:20:48.679
of convention for gamers.

00:20:48.679 --> 00:20:51.059
&gt;&gt;Jerry Holkins: Right. It can have this other
stuff -

00:20:51.059 --> 00:20:52.059
&gt;&gt;Mike Krahulik: Yeah.

00:20:52.059 --> 00:20:53.059
&gt;&gt;Jerry Holkins: That's fine.

00:20:53.059 --> 00:20:57.960
&gt;&gt;Mike Krahulik: But the focus of it should
be on video games. And I remember we started

00:20:57.960 --> 00:21:01.380
working with a company that was doing a show
back East.

00:21:01.380 --> 00:21:02.380
&gt;&gt;Jerry Holkins: Uberchan.

00:21:02.380 --> 00:21:06.480
&gt;&gt;Mike Krahulik: Called Uberchan. 'Cause we
in our minds, we have no expertise putting

00:21:06.480 --> 00:21:10.019
on shows so that what we thought is: "Well
we'll work with someone who's put on shows

00:21:10.019 --> 00:21:15.050
before. We'll just have them come over to
Seattle and help us do it." And it turned

00:21:15.050 --> 00:21:19.550
out that what they wanted to do was make an
Uberchan Seattle, instead of a Penny Arcade

00:21:19.550 --> 00:21:25.180
expo. And that, we sort of came to that conclusion
late in the -

00:21:25.180 --> 00:21:28.990
&gt;&gt;Jerry Holkins: Yeah. You mean, things had
been underway. Planning for this convention

00:21:28.990 --> 00:21:33.030
had been underway for a while before we realized
that we were talking about two completely

00:21:33.030 --> 00:21:34.030
different conventions.

00:21:34.030 --> 00:21:38.340
&gt;&gt;Mike Krahulik: Yeah. And so, I remember
they left after a meeting and we all sort

00:21:38.340 --> 00:21:43.100
of looked at each other and realized what
was, what they, what had happened and what

00:21:43.100 --> 00:21:47.559
they wanted and what we wanted, and we said
to Robert: "Can we just make our own convention?

00:21:47.559 --> 00:21:50.090
Can we do that." And it was three months later
that -

00:21:50.090 --> 00:21:51.090
&gt;&gt;Jerry Holkins: Right.

00:21:51.090 --> 00:21:56.480
