00:44:22.160 --> 00:44:30.270
a franchise. Where do you see, do you see
it as being a healthy industry or ?

00:44:30.270 --> 00:44:34.350
&gt;&gt;Mike Krahulik: What's our take on the video
game industry?

00:44:34.350 --> 00:44:35.350
&gt;&gt;Man's voice in audience: Yeah.

00:44:35.350 --> 00:44:36.350
&gt;&gt;Mike Krahulik: Jerry?

00:44:36.350 --> 00:44:44.380
&gt;&gt;Jerry Holkins: Well, one of the big problems
certainly as it ticks forward in terms of

00:44:44.380 --> 00:44:50.470
computing power, is that the games are so
expensive to make that it strips out a lot

00:44:50.470 --> 00:44:58.790
of that, a lot of that - the appetite for
risk goes down as those amounts start to creep,

00:44:58.790 --> 00:45:05.630
and that is true. That is just unfortunately
true. But I would say I haven't seen, I haven't

00:45:05.630 --> 00:45:12.720
seen, you know, what I think of as innovation
 - I haven't innovation diluted as a result.

00:45:12.720 --> 00:45:19.079
There's so many more channels for people to
execute on an independent idea. I mean as

00:45:19.079 --> 00:45:23.369
that computing power grows like, the base
of people who are creating really interesting

00:45:23.369 --> 00:45:27.950
content has grown to. Even in Flash. I mean
there's games, there's games that are based

00:45:27.950 --> 00:45:32.820
in Flash. Flash is a game platform that is
creating games with more sophistication than

00:45:32.820 --> 00:45:33.940
I played as a young person.

00:45:33.940 --> 00:45:43.280
You know what I'm saying, like the paths to
game creation are pretty broad now. Even as

00:45:43.280 --> 00:45:47.990
that, that point gets up. And this is where
we were talking about the AAA retail title.

00:45:47.990 --> 00:45:53.010
That does not represent the entire industry.
And it doesn't represent every incredible

00:45:53.010 --> 00:45:54.010
idea that comes out.

00:45:54.010 --> 00:45:59.410
I mean even like DigiPan-- like some kids
from DigiPan came up with some crazy-ass S,

00:45:59.410 --> 00:46:04.390
and that stuff, and then here comes Valve
and they, they snatched them up. I mean Valve

00:46:04.390 --> 00:46:08.210
has the wherewithal to do that. You know they
have the, they have the money-- they're in

00:46:08.210 --> 00:46:14.079
position to do that. But there's channels
like Xbox5 Indy Games and then one step up

00:46:14.079 --> 00:46:19.920
from that Xbox Live Arcade and you have PSN--,
I mean there's a lot of pretty sophisticated

00:46:19.920 --> 00:46:23.700
things coming out that are not a part of the,
you know, the industry at large.

00:46:23.700 --> 00:46:28.980
There's a lot of great ideas out there that
are still happening, MA Teams. You know what

00:46:28.980 --> 00:46:31.800
I'm saying? And then you have, like Torchlight
 ?

00:46:31.800 --> 00:46:33.570
&gt;&gt;Mike Krahulik: Yeah, Torchlight's amazing.

00:46:33.570 --> 00:46:38.010
&gt;&gt;Jerry Holkins: It's just a pure, it just
a very, very pure gaming experience. Twenty

00:46:38.010 --> 00:46:42.180
dollars, these guys made it in a year. It's
a, you know it's a local company. I mean,

00:46:42.180 --> 00:46:47.910
I just, I don't, it's you know, on the retail
shelf your game spot, yes, it's always been

00:46:47.910 --> 00:46:54.940
a haven for mediocrity. That's not a new fact.
But there is, that is absolutely not the entirety

00:46:54.940 --> 00:46:56.920
of the, of our creative outlet.

00:46:56.920 --> 00:47:04.810
&gt;&gt;Man's voice in audience: So there's gaming
companies that are into [unaudible] you like

00:47:04.810 --> 00:47:05.940
something that ?

00:47:05.940 --> 00:47:09.560
&gt;&gt;Mike Krahulik: It's happened a couple of
times. He wants to know if game companies

00:47:09.560 --> 00:47:18.890
ever come to us as a very focused, focus group?
And it's happened a couple of times, yes.

00:47:18.890 --> 00:47:23.660
A lot of times they sort of, they might not
come to us with that intention, but they end

00:47:23.660 --> 00:47:29.619
up getting it. Because we won't advertise
anything unless we play it and like it. So,

00:47:29.619 --> 00:47:33.102
you know, if a company comes to us with, I'm
trying to think of the last one, well like

00:47:33.102 --> 00:47:34.102
 ?

00:47:34.102 --> 00:47:35.102
&gt;&gt;Jerry Holkins: Like White Knight Chronicles?

00:47:35.102 --> 00:47:38.539
&gt;&gt;Mike Krahulik: Yeah. Like White Knight Chronicles
they say: "Well, do you want to advertise

00:47:38.539 --> 00:47:42.000
it?" And we say: "We have to play it first."
And so, you know, they send us the game and

00:47:42.000 --> 00:47:45.100
we play it and we're like: "Yeah, that's pretty
good. Yeah, we'll advertise that." But sometimes

00:47:45.100 --> 00:47:48.480
it doesn't go that way and so we say: "No.
It's not very good. We're not gonna advertise

00:47:48.480 --> 00:47:53.020
it." So they may not come to us wanting an
opinion, they just want ads on our site, but

00:47:53.020 --> 00:47:54.220
we tend to give it regardless

00:47:54.220 --> 00:47:57.180
&gt;&gt;Jerry Holkins: And its, it's a complicated
situation for us because there are people

00:47:57.180 --> 00:48:01.881
at Penny Arcade whose job it is to try to
populate the site with advertising. You know

00:48:01.881 --> 00:48:05.990
what I'm saying? And they're paid directly
by the amount of advertising, you know what

00:48:05.990 --> 00:48:07.059
I'm saying, like that's their job.

00:48:07.059 --> 00:48:10.360
&gt;&gt;Mike Krahulik: You sort of see them watching
us play it through the window like just praying

00:48:10.360 --> 00:48:11.360
to God that we'll like it.

00:48:11.360 --> 00:48:13.940
&gt;&gt;Jerry Holkins: It's got to be so scary for
them because we'll just say: "No." And we're

00:48:13.940 --> 00:48:17.829
basically saying: "No, you can't have any
money. No money. We're taking your money away

00:48:17.829 --> 00:48:18.829
now.

00:48:18.829 --> 00:48:21.049
&gt;&gt;Mike Krahulik: "I know you wanted that money.
