00:48:21.049 --> 00:48:22.049
[laughter]

00:48:22.049 --> 00:48:26.710
&gt;&gt;Man's voice in audience: You are in the
[inaudible]

00:48:26.710 --> 00:48:30.360
&gt;&gt;Mike Krahulik: DRM and games-- necessary
evil or ridiculous waste of time? That was

00:48:30.360 --> 00:48:31.710
the question.

00:48:31.710 --> 00:48:37.569
&gt;&gt;Jerry Holkins: This just, it's never-- it
just never lasts very long. You know they

00:48:37.569 --> 00:48:41.329
put the DRM on there and they have, you know,
they have some kind of internal study, some

00:48:41.329 --> 00:48:45.780
kind of internal numbers that say that the
first two weeks of a game are it's prime earning

00:48:45.780 --> 00:48:48.950
years-- or, you know what I'm saying like
they have an idea, they have some study and

00:48:48.950 --> 00:48:53.559
I don't know when the study is from, that
tells them that they have to apply that stuff.

00:48:53.559 --> 00:48:59.220
But it never, but I mean zero day is still
with us. Negative one day, it's, you know,

00:48:59.220 --> 00:49:04.119
a month in advance sometimes for games that
are waiting for their console versions to,

00:49:04.119 --> 00:49:05.150
you know, to appear.

